{"sections":[],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule"]]},"metadata":{"modules":[{"name":"EmacsSwiftModule"}],"role":"article","roleHeading":"Article","title":"Error Handling"},"kind":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Handling Lisp errors on Swift side and vice versa."}],"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Emacs-Errors","text":"Emacs Errors"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Emacs Lisp is a dynamically typed language, the majority of input validation and type conformance checks end up being errors. It is a normal state of things. Runtime errors in Lisp doesn’t have a stigma to them like in some other languages, especially because the user can literally call functions all the time."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In "},{"code":"EmacsSwiftModule","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", we surface Lisp runtime errors as Swift exceptions. And in the vast majority of the cases users should just re-throw errors back to the user. Again, this is normal, especially if it happens in a user-facing function. Any interaction with "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" can potentially throw. You only handle these errors yourself if you actually expect a very specific error as a possibility and have a backup plan."}]},{"text":"Swift Errors","level":2,"anchor":"Swift-Errors","type":"heading"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"At the same time, Swift code exceptions are also fine and will be translated into Emacs error signals. You probably want to handle a bigger portion of this kind of errors, but if you won’t, nothing bad will happen. If it won’t crash Emacs, it’s not critical.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"aside","name":"Important","style":"important","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"If you choose to disable error propagation via ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"try!"},{"type":"text","text":", and do get an exception, it will crash Emacs. Swift runtime errors are critical."}]}]},{"type":"heading","text":"User Interruptions","anchor":"User-Interruptions","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If your code introduces a long-running Lisp function, you should check from time to time if the user interrupted it by pressing "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"C-g"},{"text":" (or similar). In this situation, it is recommended to quit any work as soon as possible. You can check it via ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment\/interrupted()"},{"type":"text","text":" method. If you work with environment, any call to it will throw "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError\/interrupted","isActive":true},{"text":", when in this state.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Lifetime-Violations","text":"Lifetime Violations","level":2},{"inlineContent":[{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment","type":"reference"},{"text":" checks for lifetime and thread model consistency and throws ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError\/lifetimeViolation","isActive":true},{"text":" or ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError\/threadModelViolation","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":". Check "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Lifetimes","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" for more details."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/ErrorHandling","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"seeAlsoSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningAModule","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/CallingLispFunctions","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningLispFunctions","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/TypeConversions"],"generated":true,"title":"Getting started"}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/errorhandling"]}],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"patch":0,"minor":3},"references":{"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule":{"role":"collection","kind":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A Swift library to write Emacs plugins in Swift!"}],"title":"EmacsSwiftModule","type":"topic"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/CallingLispFunctions":{"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/callinglispfunctions","type":"topic","title":"Calling Lisp Functions","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/CallingLispFunctions","kind":"article","role":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Calling Lisp functions from your Swift code."}]},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/DefiningLispFunctions":{"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/defininglispfunctions","title":"Defining Lisp Functions","role":"article","kind":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningLispFunctions","type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Defining Emacs Lisp functions directly from Swift."}]},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/TypeConversions":{"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/typeconversions","type":"topic","title":"Type conversions","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/TypeConversions","kind":"article","role":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Converting Swift values into Lisp values and vice versa."}]},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/Environment":{"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Environment is the interaction point with Emacs. If you want to do anything on the Emacs side, you need to have an Environment."}],"title":"Environment","fragments":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"text":"Environment","kind":"identifier"}],"navigatorTitle":[{"text":"Environment","kind":"identifier"}],"role":"symbol","kind":"symbol","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/environment"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/EmacsError/threadModelViolation":{"title":"EmacsError.threadModelViolation","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"case"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"threadModelViolation"}],"role":"symbol","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError\/threadModelViolation","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/emacserror\/threadmodelviolation","kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Using "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" in a different thread than issued it."}],"type":"topic"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/EmacsError/interrupted":{"role":"symbol","title":"EmacsError.interrupted","fragments":[{"text":"case","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"identifier","text":"interrupted"}],"type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Emacs user interruption (C-g)."}],"kind":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/emacserror\/interrupted","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError\/interrupted"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/EmacsError/lifetimeViolation":{"role":"symbol","title":"EmacsError.lifetimeViolation","fragments":[{"text":"case","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"lifetimeViolation"}],"kind":"symbol","type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Using "},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment","type":"reference"},{"text":" outside of its scope.","type":"text"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError\/lifetimeViolation","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/emacserror\/lifetimeviolation"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/Lifetimes":{"abstract":[{"text":"Emacs internals lifetimes.","type":"text"}],"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/lifetimes","title":"Lifetimes","kind":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Lifetimes","role":"article","type":"topic"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/DefiningAModule":{"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/definingamodule","type":"topic","title":"Defining a module","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningAModule","kind":"article","role":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Defining a new Emacs module from Swift."}]},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/Environment/interrupted()":{"abstract":[{"text":"Checks whether the user interrupted execution of the current function.","type":"text"}],"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/environment\/interrupted()","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"func"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"text":"interrupted","kind":"identifier"},{"text":"() -> ","kind":"text"},{"text":"Bool","kind":"typeIdentifier","preciseIdentifier":"s:Sb"}],"title":"interrupted()","kind":"symbol","identifier":"doc:\/